50|$|Antimony-124 is {{assembled}} with beryllium to make laboratory <b>neutron</b> <b>sources</b> and startup <b>neutron</b> <b>sources.</b> Antimony-124 (half-life 60.20 days) emits β− and 1.690MeV {{gamma rays}} (also 0.602MeV and 9 fainter emissions from 0.645 to 2.090 MeV), yielding stable tellurium-124. Gamma rays from Antimony-124 knock neutrons off beryllium-9 {{with an average}} kinetic energy of 24keV, intermediate neutrons. The other product is two alpha particles.|$|R
5000|$|Primary sources, {{used for}} startup of a fresh reactor core; {{conventional}} <b>neutron</b> <b>sources</b> are used. The primary sources {{are removed from}} the reactor after the first fuel campaign, usually after few months, as neutron capture resulting from the thermal neutron flux in an operating reactor changes {{the composition of the}} isotopes used, and thus reduces their useful lifetime as <b>neutron</b> <b>sources.</b>|$|R
